<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,310,405,431]" box="[189,310,405,431]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,405,431]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,405,431]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1398,452,550]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
This species could be easily differentiated from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1920" box="[940,1121,452,478]" class="Insecta" family="Cantharidae" genus="Micropodabrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[940,1121,452,478]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Micropodabrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its brown elytra and the structures of aedaegus: ventral process of each paramere wide, laterophyses strongly sclerotized and bent dorsally at apices.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,324,589,615]" box="[189,324,589,615]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,589,615]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,589,615]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,636,698]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[717,826,636,662]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">brunneus</emphasis>
(brown) and 
<emphasis box="[982,1054,637,662]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">penna</emphasis>
(wing), referring to its brown elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
